oint branch\\n    34→+    ├── entire-logs/entire.log  # CLI structured JSON logs\\n    35→+    ├── checkpoint-metadata/    # Checkpoint + session metadata\\n    36→+    └── repo -> /tmp/...        # Symlink to preserved repo (E2E_KEEP_REPOS=1 only)\\n    37→+```\\n    38→+\\n    39→+## Preserved Repo\\n    40→+\\n    41→+When the test run was executed with `E2E_KEEP_REPOS=1`, each test's artifact directory contains a `repo` symlink pointing to the preserved temporary git repository. This is the actual repo the test operated on — you can inspect it directly.\\n    42→+\\n    43→+**Navigate via the symlink** (e.g., `{artifact-dir}/repo/`) rather than resolving the `/tmp/...` path. The symlink lives inside the artifact directory so permissions and paths stay consistent.\\n    44→+\\n    45→+The preserved repo contains:\\n    46→+- Full git history with all branches (main, `entire/checkpoints/v1`)\\n    47→+- The `.entire/` directory with CLI state, config, and raw logs\\n    48→+- The `.claude/` directory (if Claude Code was the agent)\\n    49→+- All files the agent created or modified, in their final state\\n    50→+\\n    51→+This is the most powerful debugging tool — you can run `git log`, `git diff`, `git show`, inspect `.entire/` internals, and see exactly what the CLI left behind.\\n    52→+\\n    53→+## Debugging Workflow\\n    54→+\\n    55→+### 1. Triage (if given a run directory)\\n    56→+\\n    57→+Read `report.nocolor.txt` to identify failures and their error messages. Each entry shows the test name, agent, duration, and failure output with file:line references.\\n    58→+\\n    59→+### 2. Read console.log (most important)\\n    60→+\\n    61→+Full transcript of every operation:\\n    62→+- `> claude -p \\\"...\\\" ...` — agent prompts with stdout/stderr\\n    63→+- `> git add/commit/...` — git commands\\n    64→+- `> send: ...` — interactive session inputs\\n    65→+\\n    66→+This tells you what happened chronologically.\\n    67→+\\n    68→+### 3. Read test source code\\n    69→+\\n    70→+Use the file:line from the report to find the test in `e2e/tests/`. Understand what the test expected to happen vs what console.log shows actually happened.\\n    71→+\\n    72→+### 4. Diagnose the CLI behavior\\n    73→+\\n    74→+Cross-reference console.log (what happened) with the test (what should have happened). Focus on CLI-level issues:\\n    75→+\\n    76→+| Symptom | CLI Investigation |\\n    77→+|---------|-------------------|\\n    78→+| Checkpoint not created / timeout | Check `entire-logs/entire.log` for hook invocations, phase transitions, errors |\\n    79→+| Wrong checkpoint content | Check `git-tree.txt` for checkpoint branch files, `checkpoint-metadata/` for session info |\\n    80→+| Hooks didn't fire | Check `entire.log` for missing hook entries (session-start, user-prompt-submit, stop, post-commit) |\\n    81→+| Stash/unstash problems | Check `entire.log` for stash-related log lines, `git-log.txt` for commit ordering |\\n    82→+| Attribution issues | Check `checkpoint-metadata/` for `files_touched`, session metadata for attribution data |\\n    83→+| Strategy mismatch | Check `entire.log` for `strategy` field, verify auto-commit vs manual-commit behavior |\\n    84→+\\n    85→+### 5. Deep dive files\\n    86→+\\n    87→+- **entire-logs/entire.log**: Structured JSON logs — hook lifecycle, session phases (`active` → `idle` → `ended`), warnings, errors. Key fields: `component`, `hook`, `strategy`, `session_id`.\\n    88→+- **git-log.txt**: Commit graph showing main branch, `entire/checkpoints/v1`, checkpoint initialization.\\n    89→+- **git-tree.txt**: Files at HEAD vs checkpoint branch (separated by `--- entire/checkpoints/v1 ---`).\\n    90→+- **checkpoint-metadata/**: `metadata.json` has `checkpoint_id`, `strategy`, `files_touched`, `token_usage`, and `sessions` array. Session subdirs have per-session details.\\n    91→+\\n    92→+### 6. Report findings\\n    93→+\\n    94→+Identify whether the issue is i